{
  "query": "How do plant-based and bacterial protein alternatives to fish meal compare in terms of their effect on Atlantic salmon growth rates in Norway?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on multiple studies from Norway, plant-based protein alternatives to fish meal generally result in decreased growth rates in Atlantic salmon. Six studies found reduced growth rates with plant-based diets, while three studies found similar growth rates compared to fish meal controls. Plant-based diets also showed reduced final body weights in four studies, with mixed effects on feeding efficiency - some studies showed lowered efficiency while others showed increased efficiency. Fish meal reduction studies found no significant differences in final weights.\n\nBacterial protein alternatives showed more favorable results. Two replicated controlled studies in Norway found similar growth rates when bacterial protein replaced up to 25% of fish meal, though 50% replacement resulted in lower growth rates. Another study actually reported higher growth rates with diets containing 18% and 36% bacterial protein compared to fish meal controls, suggesting bacterial protein may be superior to plant-based alternatives in maintaining salmon growth performance.",
  "action_ids": [
    "924",
    "918",
    "915"
  ]
}

