{
  "query": "What are the non-chemical alternatives for controlling sea lice on salmon farms?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the research evidence, several non-chemical alternatives exist for controlling sea lice on salmon farms. The use of cleaner wrasse as natural control agents shows mixed results - corkwing and goldskinny cleaner wrasse were found to be as effective as chemical treatments in one controlled study in Ireland, while rockcook cleaner wrasse were ineffective at preventing lice outbreaks in another study. Altering lighting conditions is another non-chemical approach, with a replicated, controlled study in Norway showing that lower numbers of lice were found on salmon kept in low intensity artificial light or natural lighting, where higher intensity artificial light led to higher lice numbers.\n\nFallowing systems represent another alternative, with a study in Scotland recording lower lice numbers on Atlantic salmon in cages using this approach, though another study in Australia found no difference in mortality from Amoebic Gill Disease where fallowing had been used. Probiotics and immunostimulants show promise - a replicated study in Scotland found increased survival in salmon fed a probiotic before bacterial exposure, while a Norwegian study found that feeding salmon a diet with 28% plant-based protein reduced lice infection by 28%, and adding beta-glucans decreased infection levels by a further 28% compared to controls.",
